This is the regular behaviour of resources linked from CSS, bootstrap isn't doing anything special here. You can try inlining them as data-uris. Instead of importing `bootstrap-sprockets` and instead use something like:

```sass
@function twbs-font-path($path) {
  @return asset-data-uri($path);
}

@function twbs-image-path($path) {
  @return image-path($path);
}

$bootstrap-sass-asset-helper: true;
```

`asset-data-uri` is [defined](https://github.com/petebrowne/sprockets-sass/blob/master/lib/sprockets/sass/functions.rb#L13) by sprockets-sass.

See my blog post on how inlining might help: http://blog.glebm.com/2013/08/28/inline-css-fonts.html

yep I just got a PoC working.  this is from the Summary class:

``` python
        class Timer(object):
            def __init__(self, summary):
                self._summary = summary

            def __enter__(self):
                self._start = time.time()

            def __exit__(self, typ, value, traceback):
                # Time can go backwards.
                self._summary.observe(max(time.time() - self._start, 0))

            def __call__(self, f):
                @wraps(f)
                def wrapped(*args, **kwargs):
                    if asyncio.iscoroutinefunction(f):
                        self.__enter__()
                        rv = f(*args, **kwargs)
                        fut = asyncio.ensure_future(rv)
                        fut.add_done_callback(lambda _: self.__exit__(None, None, None))
                        return fut
                    else:
                        with self:
                            return f(*args, **kwargs)
                return wrapped
```

You could also also do something like this in `wrapped` (note `iscoroutine` vs. `iscoroutinefunction`):

``` python
self.__enter__()
rv = f(*a, **kw)
if asyncio.iscoroutine(rv):
    rv = asyncio.ensure_future(rv)
    rv.add_done_callback(lambda _: self.__exit__(None, None, None))
else:
    self.__exit(None, None, None)
return rv
```

Of course measuring only the time they actually run is impossible as you point out. :)

You’ll have to write some helpers to abstract away asyncio…also `asyncio.ensure_future` was called `async` before 3.4.4 (which ships with Ubuntu Trusty) but can’t be async on 3.5 anymore so you may have to do some compatibility dance.

