Perhaps, though with the example you showed I would do it the other way around. Instead of:

```
struct Wavelet {
  unsigned int cwt_possible:1;
  unsigned int dwt_possible:1;
  DiscreteWavelet* discrete_wavelet;
  ContinuousWavelet* continuous_wavelet;
}

struct DiscreteWavelet {...};
struct ContinuousWavelet {...}:
```

Perhaps the following:

```
struct BaseWavelet {...};
struct DiscreteWavelet {
  BaseWavelet base;
  ...
};
struct ContinuousWavelet {
  BaseWavelet base;
  ...
};
```

This makes sure that the type hierarchy is defined by which struct a function takes, and not a boolean flag (`xyz_possible`) that is checked at runtime. Hopefully that will let the compiler catch more errors, and it'll mirror the inheritance used in the Python classes better too.

For functions that can take either a continuous or discrete wavelet, I suggest the dispatching is done in the Cython layer. Shared data that can use the same code should operate on the base wavelet struct, and if the code is significantly different separate functions are nicer anyway. We could use C11 generic functions, except we need to support MSVC.

